Why cache.

A database query takes a millisecond at best and hundreds of milliseconds under load, while an in-memory cache lookup takes microseconds, three or four orders of magnitude faster. For any read pattern where the same answer is computed over and over, putting a cache in front of the database is the single highest-leverage performance change available.

The shape is simple: the application checks the cache first, and on a hit it returns the cached value immediately; on a miss it falls through to the database, writes the result into the cache, and returns it, so subsequent requests within the cache's lifetime get the fast path.

AWS offers two services for this. The managed in-memory cache runs Redis, the newer Valkey, or Memcached, and works in front of anything. And a dedicated accelerator is a write-through cache purpose-built for the no-sequel database and only that, a drop-in for its client with no application changes. The rest of this discussion is about the general-purpose cache.
